A friend bought this for his wife and she shot it five times and didn't like it. Probably for the same reasons I DO like it! It is ultra light and has a shrouded hammer. I took it off his hands since they needed some money and weren't using this at all. I bought it just to help out but don't need it since I have several other guns that will do about the same thing. I'd like to recoup what I paid for it.

This  current production S&W Airweight .38 is rated for +P ammunition, and to me is an ideal concealed carry revolver. They always go bang when you need them to. They can be carried in a pocket without fear of snagging. You know the rest. This revolver has been shot maybe ten times and looks like new. It comes in the S&W box, with papers, etc. The DA trigger is smooth and light. I have not shot it, since I knew I wasn't going to keep it, and it looks so nice. Since this one can handle =P self defense ammunition, it's a more effective round for self defense. You don't have to worry about a hollow point jamming in a revolver!

For about the same price as a .380 that might jam on you when you REALLY need it to work - this Smith a& Wesson is a serious and high quality gun that is reliable and will never fail you. that's why they still make them, and why they are still a great and serious self defense option.

title: For Trade:  ONE OWNER RUGER GP100 6 INCH STAINLESS
postcontent: My Brother purchased this gun new in May of 90. We shot the gun the day he bought it with 6 rounds of 38 special and it went back into the safe until a few years later. He sent the pistol to Ford Guns in Florida where they dehorned all the sharp edges rounded all the corners and polished the matte stainless to a mirror finish. There is not a machine mark on the pistol and the finish looks better than any bright stainless gun or nickel gun I have ever seen. They did an amazing job. He then sent the pistol to Grant Cunningham. If you know anything about revolvers you know who this is. He gave it one of his super trigger jobs and replaced all the springs in the trigger pack and polished everything. The single action pull is SCARY and breaks at less than a pound. The double action feels like you are pulling your finger on ICE. Its as smooth as any Colt Python out there or smoother. The pistol comes with the original Ruger Grips and High Viz sights. The green is in the gun now the red and white pipe have never been taken out of the pack. The pistol also has Hogue Rosewood grips that look fantastic. Has had less than 400 rounds thru it most 38s. The lockup is super tight and the timing is perfect and the cylinder ring is very faint. The pistol will cut the same ragged hole at 15 yards freehanded. Would rather trade than sell but feel free to make offers just know that there is over 1300 invested in the pistol. Don't expect to get that out of it by any means but will also not give it away. WILL NOT RESPOND TO STUPID OFFERS! WILL ONLY TRADE FOR ITEMS LISTED BELOW! Thanks for looking.

title: For Sale:  Davenport 120 year old shotgun
postcontent:
NEW LOWER PRICE:   $90 !!!

Single barrel break open 12 gauge shotgun, 30" heavy and thick barrel, not sure what choke or chamber length. Marked "ETOWAH" on one side, but that's probably a trade name or store brand. Gun appears to be made by DAVENPORT between 1902 and 1910. Metal is in excellent condition-probably reblued. It's too pretty to be original. Stock is in very good condition, although the black plastic butt plate is a modern replacement. Gun is missing the hammer ($15, available at gunparts corp), the hammer screw, one trigger guard screw, the spring that pushes the firing pin back away from the chamber, and the brass bead at the muzzle.  This gun has the patented hinged key take-down pivot screw. The barrel steel does not look like Damascus or twist construction to me, but I'm not a gunsmith. The Davenport 1903 catalog (available on eBay) says it was offered in both Damascus steel versions and "fine decarbonized rolled steel" models.
 Bore is pitted from prior use with black powder shells or corrosive primed ammo in early 1900s.

UPDATE FOR APRIL 25th .... NEW LOWER PRICE of $90.

title: For Sale:  H&R Topper Buck slug shotgun 12 ga 3"
postcontent:
H&R single shot "Topper Buck" model 162 break-open shotgun.
12 gauge, 3" magnum chamber, 24" cylinder bore non-rifled barrel.
Comes with iron sights for use with foster style slugs.
Metal is in good condition, wood is in very good condition. Has factory original rubber recoil pad with white spacer, and has sling hardware ready for your sling or carry strap.
This is a light weight gun with a skinny fore-end wood. Good for beginners except for the serious recoil with slug or buckshot loads.  00 buckshot patterns pretty tight for an unchoked barrel. I get 8" spread at 12 yards or about 20" spread at 25 yds.

ANOTHER POSSIBLE USE for this gun would be to cut down the barrel to 18" and mount a tactical flashlight with an around-the-barrel clamp just forward of the wood, and then you have a cheap but amazingly powerful home defense weapon. Short and handy. Only good for one shot, of course, but that one shot could bring down anything on two or four legs.

FTF preferred in my area, up GA 400 about 45 minutes north of Atlanta. I could ship it to  an FFL dealer of your choice at your expense upon payment in full.

title: For Sale:  Kel-tec RFB 308 Bullpup Rifle 18 RFB18 KELTEC 7.62
postcontent:
From the factory: RFB stands for Rifle, Forward-ejecting Bullpup. Why forward-ejecting? Because it allows the RFB to be the first truly ambidextrous 7.62 NATO Bullpup ever developed. The patented, dual-extractor system maintains control of the case from the moment it leaves the magazine and upon firing, pulls the fired case from the chamber and lifts them to push them into an ejection chute above the barrel, where they exit. The Bullpup configuration and tilting-block mechanism allow the 18" model to be only 26.1" long, or as much as 14" shorter in overall length than its competitors with equal barrel lengths. Furthermore, the stock and mechanism cross-section is similar to a conventional rifle, in stark contrast to existing Bullpup rifles. The RFB is also the safest Bullpup ever developed because the breech is separated from the shooters face by two layers of 1.6 mm steel. In the highly unlikely event of a case rupture, gas expansion is directed downwards through the magazine well to protect the shooters head and face. The RFB is a short-stroke gas piston operated semi-automatic rifle in 7.62 mm NATO caliber. It accepts standard metric FAL type magazines which work "drop free" and do not need to be tilted in. One 20 round magazine is included*. Barrels on current models are 18" long, with a chrome lined bore and chamber. The muzzle is threaded 5/8x24 TPI and comes equipped with our A2-style Flash Hider*. Longer barrel lengths of 24", 26" and 32" will be available in the future. All controls are fully ambidextrous; the reciprocating operating handle can be switched to either side. The trigger mechanism is second to no other Bullpup ever built and better than nearly all commercial semi-auto rifles. The safety disconnects the trigger and blocks the hammer action. A Mil-Spec Picatinny rail is attached rigidly to the barrel. No open sights are provided, allowing the user to select from the very best new optics and sight systems available. The RFB comes with a two point sling that can be easily configured to suit the user's preference. Available accessories include a free-floating, four-sided Picatinny forend, bipod mounts, a removable bayonet lug for use with NATO style bayonets including our own Folding Bayonet, and many more.

Technical specs Calibers: Target Carbine Weight unloaded (no magazine): 11.3 lbs 8.1 lbs Length: 40" 26" Barrel length: 32" 18" Practical range: 1200m 600m
